1 patient choice, and create barriers to timely access for Medicaid recipients; and
2 WHEREAS, increasing Medicaid coverage for breast pumps from eighty dollars to
3 one hundred forty dollars may improve patient access, enhance maternal and infant health
4 outcomes, and support continued breastfeeding efforts across the state; and
5 WHEREAS, a comprehensive study by the Louisiana Department of Health would
6 assist the legislature in evaluating the fiscal impact, healthcare benefits, provider
7 participation, and patient outcomes associated with increasing breast pump reimbursement
8 and coverage rates.
9 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the Senate of the Legislature of Louisiana
10 does hereby urge and request the Louisiana Department of Health to study the impact of
11 increasing Medicaid reimbursement and coverage for breast pumps from eighty dollars to
12 one hundred forty dollars in order to improve patient access to medically necessary
13 breastfeeding equipment.
14 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the study shall include, at a minimum:
15 (1) Current breast pump utilization and access among Medicaid recipients.
16 (2) Comparative reimbursement rates in other states.
17 (3) Supplier participation and network adequacy.
18 (4) Potential maternal and infant health outcomes associated with increased access.
19 (5) Fiscal considerations and potential cost savings associated with improved
20 breastfeeding rates.
21 (6) Recommendations for legislative or administrative action.
22 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Louisiana Department of Health shall submit
23 a written report of its findings and recommendations to the Senate Committee on Health and
24 Welfare no later than February 1, 2027.
25 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that a copy of this Resolution be transmitted to the
26 secretary of the Louisiana Department of Health.
